--- !u!1001 &878974989101214266
PrefabInstance:
  m_ObjectHideFlags: 0
  serializedVersion: 2
  m_Modification:
    serializedVersion: 3
    m_TransformParent: {fileID: 2084232956}
    m_Modifications:
    - target: {fileID: 323304261447706255, guid: 1144efe1444ba9246ad4c579d7d6b873, type: 3}
      propertyPath: m_text
      value: "<color=#FFFFFF><size=64>\nThe project shown is a collection of Destructible
        Environment examples created by students at Manchester Metropolitan University
        for the Second Year 25/26: Games Development (Thematic Project). Students
        were paired into allocated groups to create a functional project based on
        a topic assigned by the course lead. This Unity project shows the completed
        group task of the assessment in alignment with University regulations, created
        using Unity, industry-standard IDEs, Discord for communication, and Trello
        for planning and sprint management.\n\nOur development process closely mirrors
        Tuckman's model of group development. During the Forming stage, the team
        oriented itself around the brief - exploring what destructible environments
        meant in practice, referencing existing examples such as Minecraft and known
        industry standard game mechanics, and settling on Unity as the engine. Task
        boundaries were defined and responsibilities began to take shape.\n \nThe
        Storming stage emerged naturally as the team debated which destructible techniques
        were worth pursuing. Dynamic Slicing, Marching Cubes, and Voxel-based destruction
        represent fundamentally different implementations, and aligning on scope
        and ownership required negotiation. Trello sprints provided a structured
        outlet for this, keeping conflict productive rather than disruptive.\n\nDuring
        the Norming stage, our  team established shared conventions - sprint structure,
        scene ownership, version control strategy, and UI design responsibilities.
        Members who focused on project management and UI design provided the scaffolding
        that allowed the technical work to progress cohesively.\n\nFinally, in the
        Performing stage, our team functioned as an effective unit. Each member worked
        autonomously on their area whether that was Dynamic Slicing, Marching Cubes,
        Voxel destruction, or the overarching UI \u2014 while the project remained
        coherent as a whole, culminating in the multi-scene tech demo presented here.\n\r"
      objectReference: {fileID: 0}
